Autoencoders¶

In [ ]:
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Flatten(),
                                     nn.Linear(784, 512),
                                     nn.ReLU(),
                                     nn.Linear(512, 256),
                                     nn.ReLU(),
                                     nn.Linear(256, 128),
                                     nn.ReLU(),
                                     nn.Linear(128, 30))
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(30, 128),
                                     nn.ReLU(),
                                     nn.Linear(128, 256),
                                     nn.ReLU(),
                                     nn.Linear(256, 784))

    def forward(self, x):
        h = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h)
        return x_hat
In [ ]:
model = AutoEncoder()
In [ ]:
criterion = nn.MSELoss()
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr = 0.001)
In [ ]:
train_costs = []
val_costs = []

for epoch in range(2):  # loop over the dataset multiple times

    running_loss = 0.0
    for i, data in enumerate(train_loader, 0):
        # get the inputs; data is a list of [inputs, labels]
        inputs, labels = data

        # zero the parameter gradients
        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # forward + backward + optimize
        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, inputs.view(-1, 28*28))
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        if i % 200 == 0:
          train_costs.append(loss.item())
          for j, data in enumerate(val_loader, 0):
            inputs, labels = data
            outputs = model(inputs)
            val_loss = criterion(outputs, inputs.view(-1, 28*28))
            val_costs.append(val_loss.item())
          # Print Loss
          print('Epoch: {}. Iteration: {}. Train Loss: {}. Validation Loss: {}'.format(epoch, i, loss.item(), val_loss.item()))

print('Finished Training')

Experimenting with hidden units of varying sizes¶

In [ ]:
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, latent_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Flatten(),
                                     nn.Linear(784, latent_dim))
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(latent_dim, 784))

    def forward(self, x):
        h = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h)
        return x_hat

Convolutional Autoencoders¶

Unpooling + Deconvolution¶

In [ ]:
class Encoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 8, 3)
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(8, 16, 3)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(16, 16, 3)
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x, idx1 = self.pool1(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x, idx2 = self.pool2(x)
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x, idx3 = self.pool3(x)
        return x, idx1, idx2, idx3
In [ ]:
class Decoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 16, 3)
        self.conv2 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 16, 3)
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxUnpool2d(3, 2)
        self.conv3 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 8, 3)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxUnpool2d(2)
        self.conv4 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(8, 1, 3)
        
    def forward(self, x, idx1, idx2, idx3):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.pool1(x, idx2)
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x = self.pool2(x, idx1)
        x = self.conv4(x)
        return x
In [ ]:
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = Encoder()
        self.decoder = Decoder()

    def forward(self, x):
        h, idx1, idx2, idx3 = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h, idx1, idx2, idx3)
        return x_hat

Deconvolution¶

In [ ]:
class Encoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 8, 3)
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(8, 16, 3)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(16, 16, 3)
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x, idx1 = self.pool1(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x, idx2 = self.pool2(x)
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x, idx3 = self.pool3(x)
        return x, idx1, idx2, idx3
In [ ]:
class Decoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 16, 10)
        self.conv2 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 16, 7)
        self.conv3 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 16, 5)
        self.conv4 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 8, 5)
        self.conv5 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(8, 8, 3)
        self.conv6 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(8, 1, 3)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x = self.conv4(x)
        x = self.conv5(x)
        x = self.conv6(x)
        return x

class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = Encoder()
        self.decoder = Decoder()

    def forward(self, x):
        h, idx1, idx2, idx3 = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h)
        return x_hat

In [ ]:
class Encoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, 8, 3)
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(8, 16, 3)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(16, 16, 3)
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, return_indices = True)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x, idx1 = self.pool1(x)
        x = self.conv2(x)
        x, idx2 = self.pool2(x)
        x = self.conv3(x)
        x, idx3 = self.pool3(x)
        return x, idx1, idx2, idx3

class Decoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxUnpool2d(7)

        # self.pool3 = nn.MaxUnpool2d(4, 2)

        x = self.pool1(x, idx3)
        # x = self.pool2(x, idx2)
        # x = x[:, :8, :, :]
        # x = self.pool3(x, idx1)
        return x.view(-1, 1, 28, 28)

Denoising Autoencoders¶

In [ ]:
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, latent_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Flatten(),
                                     nn.Linear(784, latent_dim))
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(latent_dim, 784))

    def forward(self, x):
        h = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h)
        return x_hat

  1. When an image with random noise is passed through a standard autoencoder, the reconstruction accuracy goes down. But a denoising autoencoder doe a good job of reconstructing the original image. Thus adding noise acts as a regularizer
  2. As the standard deviation of the noise increases, the reconstruction accuracy and the reconstructed image quality decreases. This can be confirmed by visual inspection

Sparse Autoencoders¶

In [ ]:
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, latent_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Flatten(),
                                     nn.Linear(784, latent_dim))
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(latent_dim, 784))

    def forward(self, x):
        h = self.encoder(x)
        x_hat = self.decoder(h)
        return h, x_hat

  idx = random.randint(0, len(mnist_data_test) - 1)

  image_hat = outputs[idx].view(28, 28)
  ax[r, c].imshow(image)

criterion_1 = nn.MSELoss()
criterion_2 = nn.L1Loss()
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr = 0.001)
In [ ]:
train_costs = []
val_costs = []

for epoch in range(5):  # loop over the dataset multiple times

    running_loss = 0.0
    for i, data in enumerate(train_loader, 0):
        # get the inputs; data is a list of [inputs, labels]
        inputs, labels = data

        # zero the parameter gradients
        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # forward + backward + optimize
        hidden, outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion_1(outputs, inputs.view(-1, 28*28)) + alpha * criterion_2(hidden, torch.zeros(*hidden.shape))
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        if i % 200 == 0:
          train_costs.append(loss.item())
          for j, data in enumerate(val_loader, 0):
            inputs, labels = data
            hidden, outputs = model(inputs)
            val_loss = criterion_1(outputs, inputs.view(-1, 28*28)) + alpha * criterion_2(hidden, torch.zeros(*hidden.shape)) 
            val_costs.append(val_loss.item())
          # Print Loss
          print('Epoch: {}. Iteration: {}. Train Loss: {}. Validation Loss: {}'.format(epoch, i, loss.item(), val_loss.item()))

print('Finished Training')

As the regularization constant decreases, the reconstruction accuracy increases. Hence, the quality of reconstructed images increases as the regularization constant decreases. But we should make sure that the regularization constant is not too low so that the over-determined network learns an identity mapping
